Read in Unabomber, output structure

The data are originally in a large character format with 3221 elements; each of these elements is a line of the document, including blank spaces/paragraph breaks, as well as full sentences or parts of sentences.

Im now going to run my cleaning genie to create a dataframe of all of the words in the document, and then show the cleaned version in a Quanteda corpus.

Clean the text

melanie_cleaner <- function(data) {
  # Normalize apostrophes and quotation marks first
  x <- str_replace_all(data, "[\u2018\u2019\u2032\u0027\u00b4\u201b]", "'") # Manage type of apostrophes to be straight
  x <- str_replace_all(x, "[\u201c\u201d\u0022\u2033\u02dd\u201f\u201e]", "[\u0022]") # Manage type of quotations to be straight
    
  # Apply contractions replacement (only for non-NA values) (search x for contractions, replace with replacement phrase)
  x <- ifelse(is.na(x), x, str_replace_all(x, setNames(replacements_25$replacement, replacements_25$word)))

  # Normalize possessives, common phrases or shortenings, roman numerals
  x <- gsub("and/or", "and or", x) # Replace and/or with and or
  x <- gsub("\\bi\\.e\\.(?=\\W|$)", "that is", x, perl = TRUE) # Replace with full phrase (unsure if to make one word)
  x <- gsub("\\betc\\.(?=\\W|$)", "etcetera", x, perl = TRUE) # Note, unsure if to make one word
  x <- gsub("vis-a-vis(?=\\W|$)", "visavis", x, perl = TRUE) # Note, unsure if to make one word
  x <- gsub("\\be\\.g\\.(?=\\W|$)", "for example", x, perl = TRUE) # Note, unsure if to make one word
  x <- gsub("\\bMr\\.(?=\\W|$)", "mister", x, perl = TRUE) # Mr., Mrs, Dr., etc fixes below
  x <- gsub("\\bMrs\\.(?=\\W|$)", "missus", x, perl = TRUE)
  x <- gsub("\\bMs\\.(?=\\W|$)", "miss", x, perl = TRUE)
  x <- gsub("\\bSr\\.(?=\\W|$)", "senior", x, perl = TRUE)
  x <- gsub("\\bJr\\.(?=\\W|$)", "junior", x, perl = TRUE)
  x <- gsub("\\bSte\\.(?=\\W|$)", "suite", x, perl = TRUE)
  x <- gsub("\\bCapt\\.(?=\\W|$)", "captain", x, perl = TRUE)
  x <- gsub("\\bProf\\.(?=\\W|$)", "professor", x, perl = TRUE)
  x <- gsub("\\bRev\\.(?=\\W|$)", "reverend", x, perl = TRUE)
  x <- gsub("'s\\b", "", x) # Remove singular and plural possessives 
  x <- gsub("s'\\b", "s", x)
  x <- gsub("\\b[IVXLCDM]+(?=[[:punct:]]|\\s|$)", " ", x, perl = TRUE) # Remove any roman numerals
  x <- gsub("\\bSt\\.(?=\\s+[A-Z])", "saint", x, perl = TRUE) # Saint (religious / place names), usually followed by capital letter for name
  x <- gsub("\\bSt\\.(?=\\s*[a-z0-9]|\\W|$)", "street", x, perl = TRUE) # Street (addresses), usually followed by non-capital letter or punctuation
  x <- gsub("\\bDr\\.(?=\\s+[A-Z])", "doctor", x, perl = TRUE) # Doctor, usually followed by capital letter for name
  x <- gsub("\\bDr\\.(?=\\s*[a-z0-9]|\\W|$)", "drive", x, perl = TRUE) # Drive (addresses), usually followed by non-capital letter or punctuation

  
  # Dashes / hyphens
  # # Merge words to retain meaning, even if spaces around dash
  x <- gsub("\\b(re|co|de|ex|pro|anti|non|self|pre|post|un|trans|quasi|dis|im|auto|hyper|neo|under|over|sub|mis|poly|mal|in|inter|com|bi|counter|be|good|to|with|a|al|be|for|fore|out)\\s*-\\s*",
            "\\1",x, ignore.case = TRUE, perl = TRUE) 
  x <- gsub("(?<=\\p{L})-(?=\\p{L})", " ", x, perl = TRUE) # Make any other words without above prefixes into standalone words
  
  # Alternative treatments for hyphens/dashes:
  # Merge words to retain meaning, even if spaces around dash
  # x <- gsub("\\b([A-Z][a-z]+)-([A-Za-z][a-z]+)(?=\\W|$)", "\\1\\2", x, perl = TRUE)
  # x <- gsub("-", " ", x) # Any remaining hyphens removed
  
  # Punctuation cleanup, lowercase, squish data and remove white space
  x <- gsub("\t|[[:punct:]]+", " ", x) # Remove tabs, punctuation, account for any missing spaces between punctuation
  x <- str_to_lower(x) # Lowercase everything
  x <- stri_remove_empty(x) # Remove any empty spaces between words, line breaks, etc.
  x <- str_squish(x)
  
  # Removal of any numbers
  x <- gsub("\\b(\\d+)(st|nd|rd|th)\\b", "\\1", x, perl = TRUE) # Remove any letters after numbers
  x <- gsub("[[:digit:]]", "", x) # Remove digits 
  
  # Lemmatizing... 
  
    # Begin df of raw and lemma words
  x <- tibble(text = x) |>
    unnest_tokens(word_raw, text) |>  # word_raw is raw word
    dplyr::mutate(word_lemma = textstem::lemmatize_words(word_raw))
  
    # Remove number and stop words
  stopwords <- tolower(Temple_stops25$word) # Stopwords to remove 
  
    # Numbers / stem words to remove
  number_stems <- "\\b(zero|one|two|three|four|five|six|seven|eight|nine|ten|eleven|twelve|thirteen|fourteen|fifteen|sixteen|seventeen|eighteen|nineteen|twenty|thirty|forty|fifty|sixty|seventy|eighty|ninety|hundred|thousand|million|billion)"
  
    # Additional words to remove (customize to case)
  extra_remove_words <- c("tm")
  
    # Stop and number word removal if requested (now keeps NAs)
  x <- x |>
    dplyr::mutate(word_clean = dplyr::case_when(
      word_lemma %in% extra_remove_words ~ NA_character_,
      stringr::str_detect(word_lemma, number_stems) ~ NA_character_, 
      word_lemma %in% stopwords ~ NA_character_,
      stringr::str_detect(word_lemma, "\\d") ~ NA_character_, # Remove digits again, just in case
      nchar(word_lemma) <= 1 ~ NA_character_, # Remove any single letters
      TRUE ~ word_lemma))
  
    # Count raw word frequency (before cleaning)
  df_raw <- x |>
    dplyr::count(word_raw, word_lemma, word_clean, name = "n_raw", sort = TRUE)
  
    # Count of how often word survives cleaning and join into one df
  df_clean <- x |>
    dplyr::filter(!is.na(word_clean)) |>
    dplyr::count(word_raw, name = "n_clean")
  df <- df_raw |>
    dplyr::left_join(df_clean, by = "word_raw")
  
  
  # Two dataframe outputs: Token-level and type-level
  
  # Token level df preserves the order of words
  token_df <- x |>
    dplyr::group_by(word_raw) |>
    dplyr::mutate(n_raw = n()) |>
    dplyr::ungroup() |>
    dplyr::group_by(word_clean) |>
    dplyr::mutate(n_clean = ifelse(is.na(word_clean), NA_integer_, n())) |>
    dplyr::ungroup()
  
  # Type level df collapses across tokens and has number count
  type_df <- token_df |>
    dplyr::count(word_raw, word_lemma, word_clean, name = "n_raw", sort = TRUE) |>
    dplyr::left_join(
      token_df |>
        dplyr::filter(!is.na(word_clean)) |>
        dplyr::count(word_raw, name = "n_clean"),
      by = "word_raw")
  
  # Return both dfs
  list(token_df = token_df, type_df = type_df)

}

output <- melanie_cleaner(unabomb)

unabomb_tokendf <- output$token_df
unabomb_typedf  <- output$type_df

The output of my cleaner are two dataframes. The type-level df has 5 columns: the original word (word_raw), the lemmatized word (word_lemma), the lemmatized word not categorized as a stop word (word_clean), the number of instances of the original word in the text (n_raw) and the number of instances of the clean word in the text (n_clean). It is collapsed across words. The token-level df has the same 5 columns, but preserves the order of the words in the text, needed for lexical dispersion later.

Import cleaned version into Quanteda

Now that Ive cleaned the text, I need to amend this output to be compatible with Quantedas corpus function, which expects a continous text as input, not a dataframe like what I have above. Im going to reconstruct the text in the proper word order using the unabomb_tokendf with only the clean words, and then look at it using Quanteda.

# Next, put into Quanteda corpus
unabomb_corpus <- corpus(unabomb_text)
summary(unabomb_corpus)
## Corpus consisting of 1 document, showing 1 document:
## 
##   Text Types Tokens Sentences

By removing the stop words and lemmatizing words, the manifesto looks pretty different. Now unabomb_corpus is the Quanteda corpus, consisting of a single text, with 2946 types (unique words) and 19255 tokens (total words, albeit cleaned).

Lets look at how the document changed by comparing pre- to post-cleaning corpora.

Table of lexical characteristics pre- and post-cleaning

Now, lets look at TTR (type-token ratio for proportion of unique words) and some other stats to see lexical diversity and distributions.

library(quanteda.textstats)
# First, make a corpus of the original text and look at it
pre_corp <- corpus(unabomb) # Making a corpus of the original imported document
# summary(pre_corp)
# Output shows 3321 documents (AKA lines of text in this case), and the number of types, tokens, and "sentences" 
# (e.g., blank lines are 0 sentences; words of any kind are 1 sentence, and for each punctuation mark in a line, 
# another "sentence" is tacked on with Quanteda) 

# This needs to be changed to collapse all of the documents into a single text, otherwise the tables of the pre- and post-cleaning
# texts will be very difficult to compare... 3000+ rows compared to 1 row. 

# Collapse all "documents" into a single one
pre_corp <- corpus(paste(unabomb, collapse = " ")) # Join every element (line) of unabomb vector into a single string with a space between each
summary(pre_corp)
## Corpus consisting of 1 document, showing 1 document:
## 
##   Text Types Tokens Sentences
##  text1  4849  38997      1792
summary(unabomb_corpus)
## Corpus consisting of 1 document, showing 1 document:
## 
##   Text Types Tokens Sentences
##  text1  2946  19255         1

Comparing corpuses, we see that the number of types (unique words) has nearly halved post-cleaning, and the main text has also shortened by about 1/3 (tokens, total words). We also adjusted the cleaned corpus so that it interprets the entirety of the corpus as once sentence given the lack of punctuation.

# Tokenize for lexical characteristics
pre_tokens <- quanteda::tokens(pre_corp, remove_punct = TRUE, remove_numbers = TRUE, remove_separators = TRUE)

# Create document feature matrix
pre_dfm <- dfm(pre_tokens)

# Lexical diversity statistics pre-cleaning
# print(textstat_lexdiv(pre_tokens, measure = c("TTR", "C", "R", "CTTR", "U", "S", "K", "I", "D", "Vm", "Maas"), log.base = 10))
print(textstat_lexdiv(pre_dfm, measure = c("TTR", "C", "R", "CTTR", "U", "S", "K", "I", "D", "Vm", "Maas"), log.base = 10))
##   document       TTR        C        R     CTTR        U         S        K
## 1    text1 0.1219891 0.798419 22.52179 15.92531 22.48507 0.8510397 93.24418
##          I           D         Vm      Maas     lgV0    lgeV0
## 1 1.591558 0.009324692 0.09546338 0.2108885 6.010415 13.83949
# Tokenize for lexical characteristics
post_tokens <- quanteda::tokens(unabomb_corpus, remove_punct = TRUE, remove_numbers = TRUE, remove_separators = TRUE)

# Create document feature matrix
post_dfm <- dfm(post_tokens)

# Lexical diversity statistics post-cleaning
# print(textstat_lexdiv(post_tokens, measure = c("TTR", "C", "R", "CTTR", "U", "S", "K", "I", "D", "Vm", "Maas"), log.base = 10))
print(textstat_lexdiv(post_dfm, measure = c("TTR", "C", "R", "CTTR", "U", "S", "K", "I", "D", "Vm", "Maas"), log.base = 10))
##   document       TTR         C        R     CTTR        U         S        K
## 1    text1 0.1529992 0.8097088 21.23054 15.01226 22.51572 0.8549288 30.35697
##          I           D         Vm      Maas     lgV0    lgeV0
## 1 7.601023 0.003035855 0.05242317 0.2107449 5.911801 13.61242

We see that pre-cleaning, 12% of words are unique, and post-cleaning 15% of words are unique per the TTR. C, R, CTTR, U, and S are also concerned with token-type ratio, essentially, lexical diversity, and remained fairly similarly pre- to post-cleaning. Yules K changed a lot from pre- (93) to post- (30), with a higher K value (or lower lexical diversity/increased concentration of words) observed in the pre- as compared to the post-cleaning text; this makes sense, as frequently repeated stop words were removed in cleaning. Yules I is the inverse of K and measures the distribution of words, with the higher I of post-cleaning (7.6) as compared to pre-cleaning (1.6) indicating that there is more repetition of words, which makes sense again with evenly distributed stop words still extant in the pre-cleaning corpus.

Lexical dispersion plot of 5 words of interest

Now, lets do a lexical dispersion plot of 5 words Id expect the Unabomber to probably talk about based on what I know about his reasoning for the crimes, and also if he talks about any of the bombs or outcomes of his actions.

library(quanteda.textplots)
names(unabomb_corpus) <- "Unabomber Manifesto"

#uses library quanteda.textplots
textplot_xray(
    kwic(quanteda::tokens(unabomb_corpus), pattern = "society"), # We live in a society
    kwic(quanteda::tokens(unabomb_corpus), pattern = "industr*"), # Anything with industry as root
    kwic(quanteda::tokens(unabomb_corpus), pattern = "environment*"), # Touch grass 
    kwic(quanteda::tokens(unabomb_corpus), pattern = "bomb"), # What he did, so does he talk about it
    kwic(quanteda::tokens(unabomb_corpus), pattern = "kill*"), # What he did, so does he talk about it
    kwic(quanteda::tokens(unabomb_corpus), pattern = "mail*"), # How he sent weapons, does he talk about it
    scale = "absolute"
)

Notice I put an * after some of the word roots, like industrial or industry. This captures all versions of the word. He talks a lot about society and industry, which he was concerned about. I also have heard hes an eco-terrorist of sorts, given that he lived in a cabin in rural Montana, and environment and its variants are fairly well distributed throughout the text, not as much as society or industry though. He also does mention bomb and kill, though rarely. He never mentions mail, which was his modus operandi. This suggests that the manifesto is more concerned with explaining his take on society and its systems in this manifesto, rather than detailing his crimes.

Wordcloud

Now, Im going to make a word cloud of the top 50 words out of the cleaned data, with larger words indicating that the word more often appears in the text.

library(RColorBrewer)
quanteda.textplots::textplot_wordcloud(post_dfm, random_order = FALSE, rotation = 0,
                                       color = brewer.pal(12, "Paired"), max_words = 50) #word cloud or another way

Have is the top word, which makes sense given the lemmatization of the cleaned data. Prominent nouns are system, society, people, power, and technology, again, checking out for this document being his diatribe on present systems.
